User: Write JavaScript to create a new `<li>` element with the text "New Item" and append it to a `<ul>` with the ID "itemList".

<thinking>
The user wants to create and append a new DOM element. I need to use `document.createElement` to create the `<li>`, set its `textContent`, select the `<ul>` element, and then use `appendChild` to add the new element.
</thinking>

<blueprint>
// JavaScript DOM manipulation
Test 'append_list_item' {
  const newItem = document.createElement('li');
  newItem.textContent = 'New Item';
  const list = document.getElementById('itemList');
  list.appendChild(newItem);
}
</blueprint>

User: Write JavaScript to add or remove the CSS class "is-active" on a `<div>` with the ID "menu" each time a button is clicked.

<thinking>
The user wants to toggle a CSS class on an element. The `classList.toggle()` method is perfect for this. I will set up a click event listener on a button that triggers this toggle on the menu div.
</thinking>

<blueprint>
// JavaScript DOM manipulation
Test 'toggle_css_class' {
  const button = document.getElementById('toggleButton'); // Assuming a button with this ID exists
  const menu = document.getElementById('menu');
  button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    menu.classList.toggle('is-active');
  });
}
</blueprint>

